<h2>Motivation</h2>
<div class="contentblock">

  <div class="textblock">
    <p>
      Membrane proteins play a crucial role for the recognition and binding of modulators and associated proteins. Due to difficulties in overexpression and crystallization, their tertiary structure is often predicted using computational methods [{'punta07'|ref}]. The prediction of solvent-accessible vs. solvent-exposed residues is a useful approach for the low resolution tertiary structure modelling of helical membrane proteins [{'hildebrand06'|ref}].
 <br/>

Starting from a given protein sequence, secondary and tertiary structure information is calculated by RHYTHM within only a few seconds. To account for different 
packing motifs the program uses various approaches for the prediction of channels and transporters (<i>channels</i>) or other membrane proteins 
(<i>membrane-coils</i>), respectively [{'hildebrand08'|ref}]. The prediction applies structural information from a growing data base of precalculated <a 
href="data/protein_data.zip">packing files</a> and evolutionary information from sequence patterns conserved in a represantative dataset of membrane proteins (<a 
href="./index.php?site=methods&sub=databases">pfam-domains</a>).
    </p>
    
